<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="111" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[189,310,264,290]" box="[189,310,264,290]" pageId="2" pageNumber="111">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,264,290]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="2" pageNumber="111" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,264,290]" pageId="2" pageNumber="111">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[188,1399,311,513]" pageId="2" pageNumber="111">
Operculum completely divided into two free lobes. Two rows of opercular paleae. Outer paleae arranged in semicircles, with straight or slightly curved, cylindrical blades and smooth or serrated margins. Inner paleae arranged in one row along inner margin of opercular lobes with straight and cylindrical blades. One pair of nuchal hooks without limbation. Multiple tentacular filaments (compound). Median ridge with lateral eyespots. Median organ cylindrical, tip truncate or tapered. Four parathoracic segments (
<bibRefCitation author="Kirtley D. W." box="[197,351,487,513]" pageId="2" pageNumber="111" refId="ref15203" refString="Kirtley D. W. 1994. A Review and Taxonomic Revision of the Family Sabellariidae Johnston, 1865 (Annelida: Polychaeta). Sabecon Press Science Series, Stuart, Florida." type="book" year="1994">Kirtley 1994</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Capa M. &amp; Hutchings P." box="[363,653,487,513]" pageId="2" pageNumber="111" pagination="144 - 163" refId="ref14623" refString="Capa M. &amp; Hutchings P. 2019. Sabellariidae Johnston, 1865. In: Helmcke J. G., Starck D., Wermuth H., Purschke G., Boggemann M. &amp; Westheide W. (eds) Handbook of Zoology, Annelida, Vol. 2: Pleistoannelida, Sedentaria II: 144 - 163. De Gruyter, Berlin, Germany." type="journal article" year="2019">Capa &amp; Hutchings 2019</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
